[3] Serology, domestic livestock, Saudi Arabia, 2010-2013
Date: Thu 12 Dec 2013
Source: Eurosurveillance, Vol 18 (50) [summ., edited]
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=20659


Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) coronavirus seroprevalence in domestic livestock in Saudi Arabia, 2010 to 2013
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract:

In Saudi Arabia, including regions of Riyadh and Al Ahsa, pseudoparticle neutralisation (ppNT) and microneutralisation (MNT) tests detected no antibodies to Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) in sheep (n=100), goats (n=45), cattle (n=50) and chickens (n=240). Dromedary camels however, had a high prevalence of MERS-CoV antibodies.

Bovine coronavirus (BCoV) infected sera from cattle had no cross-reactivity in MERS-CoV ppNT or MNT, while many dromedary camels' sera reacted to both BCoV and MERS-CoV. Some nevertheless displayed specific serologic reaction profiles to MERS-CoV.

[Authors: Hemida MG, Perera RA, Wang P, Alhammadi MA, Siu LY, Li M, Poon LL, Saif L, Alnaeem A, Peiris M]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As rightly indicated in the editorial note above, more studies are needed to elucidate animal-human links, as exposure to animals has only been documented for a limited number of human MERS cases.

In the meantime, the veterinary authorities remain with uncertainties in relation to precautionary measures to be applied. Saudi Arabia reported in its OIE notification of 28 Nov 2013 that "all animals [in the holding involved] were kept under observation and quarantine and all were apparently healthy." It will be interesting to note what was done there since.

The following extract from a Bahrain media report, dated 3 Dec 2013, may illustrate the dilemma of public and animal health authorities (thanks to ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall):

"The Prime Minister issued directives to the Ministry of Municipalities Affairs and Urban Planning to tighten control procedures on livestock and camels imported and to ensure they are free of diseases prior to allowing them into the country for the purpose of safeguarding the citizens' safety and protecting domestic livestock. He ordered the aforementioned Ministry to investigate 30 camels imported by a livestock trader from a Gulf State. In light of the information that Bahrain's Health Ministry received from a Gulf State's Health Ministry that stated that the camels were suspected to have been infected with coronavirus that they were immediately executed by the Municipalities Affairs Ministry. HRH Premier directed the Municipalities Affairs Ministry to take necessary legal action to suspend the said merchant's license until the investigation is completed" (see at http://www.bna.bh/portal/en/news/591367).

It may be assumed that similar dilemmas prevail in other countries in the region, prescribing the need for some advice from international authorities on possible elementary precautionary measures even at the current early stage of investigations, and underlining the urgent need for further studies. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1HAJ.]
